text.tspan: Match banner image from print publication
Introduce the reader to the Heartland
Descriptive map title: lorem ipsum dolor sit amet,
consectetur adipiscing elit, aenean id suscipit nisi
Map definition title: Indicatory, geographies, 2010 to 2016
This is the state-level view of an indicator; it covers state aggregates (total and rural)
States are shaded according to performance
Bar chart shows distribution, benchmarking against Heartland/Non-Heartland averages and other states
Bar chart will also function as legend; breaks in colors/groupings would be labeled with values
User can hover over map or bar chart to pull up three things: 1) geo name, 2) change value, 3) point in time level
This is not the primary interface for retrieving a place's data
For metro/micro area maps, I propose using points (dots) to place the geographies on the map and sizing them
by population or other appropriate scale variable (e.g. gross product, employment, etc.) The map will need to be
zoomable to facilitate highlighting places on the map. Also note that for micro areas, with arount ~300 observations
the bars in the chart will be extremely narrow. The chart will still be useful for displaying the distribution, but the
user will have difficulty interacting with it (trying to hover).
For mobile users, my inclination is to knock out the maps and simply display the bar chart. This will give a quick
readout of the distribution of values and comparison to non-heartland
Stamp out additional map/bar chart modules for each
outcome and driver category (so ~7 of these modules)
Map definition title: Indicatory, geographies, 2010 to 2016
Please don't worry about the color
choices here as I've not given them
1) Intro, 2-4) Each outcome category, 5-8) Each driver category, 9) Dashboard, 10) Conclusion
